          Programming note: Money Stuff will be off tomorrow and Monday, ba=
ck on Tuesday.=C2=A0Also, Bloomberg is doing a survey of=C2=A0Money Stuff r=
eaders; please take a few minutes to fill it out if you haven=E2=80=99t yet=
. Thanks!

 =20
   =20
      Sculptor
   =20
 =20

Sculptor Capital Management Inc. is a publicly traded hedge fund firm that =
has agreed to sell itself to Rithm Capital Corp., another investment manage=
r, for $11.15 per share. Since Sculptor signed the Rithm deal in July, anot=
her bidder has emerged: a group of mostly hedge fund managers, led by Boaz =
Weinstein and including Marc Lasry and Bill Ackman, who want to buy Sculpto=
r with their personal funds, and who put in a bid earlier this month for $1=
2.25. So far, though, Sculptor has said no: Its board of directors is stick=
ing with the $11.15 Rithm deal rather than taking, or even really discussin=
g, the $12.25 Weinstein deal.
We have   discussed this   several times in the   last two   weeks. Sculpto=
r says that the Weinstein deal is too uncertain: It=E2=80=99s not clear tha=
t they have the money, and they might scare off Sculptor=E2=80=99s hedge fu=
nd clients, which would kill the deal. The Weinstein investors say =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0well, they don=E2=80=99t say much. Weinstein=C2=A0signed a nondisc=
losure agreement earlier in Sculptor=E2=80=99s sale process, preventing him=
 from making public bids or other public statements about the deal, so most=
 of what we know about his bid comes from Sculptor=E2=80=99s statements. Bu=
t Dan Och, Sculptor=E2=80=99s estranged founder, does not have an NDA, and =
he has been kibbitzing publicly on the deal;=C2=A0his=C2=A0version of event=
s is that Sculptor=E2=80=99s board prefers the Rithm deal because Rithm wou=
ld keep Jimmy Levin, Sculptor=E2=80=99s current chief executive officer and=
 chief investment officer (and Och=E2=80=99s bitterly estranged ex-prot=C3=
=A9g=C3=A9), to run Sculptor=E2=80=99s funds, while Weinstein would not. In=
 Och=E2=80=99s telling, the board is too close to Levin, and is putting his=
 interests over those of shareholders. (Och,   as we have discussed, has hi=
s own interests, which are not quite the same as those of public shareholde=
rs.)
Yesterday evening,  Sculptor announced that the Weinstein group put in a ne=
w offer for $12.76 per share, raising its own offer by 51 cents. Sculptor=
=C2=A0still says no: =E2=80=9CNotwithstanding its proposed price of $12.76 =
per Class A Share, the Special Committee cannot support a transaction that =
has significantly less certainty of closing than the transaction with Rithm=
.=E2=80=9D
Reading between the lines of the announcement you can see that Weinstein di=
dn=E2=80=99t just raise his price, he also answered some of Sculptor=E2=80=
=99s previous complaints about certainty. Sculptor=E2=80=99s board original=
ly objected to the Weinstein proposal because it didn=E2=80=99t have commit=
ted financing for the full $650 million or so required to do the deal:
=09Weinstein and friends provided equity commitment letters for $288 millio=
n.=09They planned to sell off Sculptor=E2=80=99s collateralized loan obliga=
tion business, roughly one-third of the firm, to another buyer (called =E2=
=80=9CBidder H=E2=80=9D in  Sculptor=E2=80=99s proxy). But they didn=E2=80=
=99t have a signed deal with Bidder H, and their deal was conditional on ge=
tting it done; Sculptor worried that they wouldn=E2=80=99t be able to.=09So=
mehow their calculation of how much money they=E2=80=99d need was too low b=
y $217 million, leaving a funding gap.

The new proposal seems to resolve those issues
  [1]
:
=09Weinstein and friends are still providing equity commitments.=09Their de=
al is no longer contingent on selling the CLO business to Bidder H. Presuma=
bly they still plan to sell it, but if they can=E2=80=99t that=E2=80=99s th=
eir problem.=09Instead, Weinstein and friends will bridge the CLO business =
by lending themselves the money: =E2=80=9CMembers of the Consortium are pro=
viding the debt commitments for its proposed debt financing.=E2=80=9D That =
is, the deal will be funded by (roughly) half equity commitments from Weins=
tein and friends, and half=C2=A0loans=C2=A0from them. If they sell the CLO =
business quickly, they=E2=80=99ll use the money to pay back the loans. If n=
ot, they=E2=80=99ll be stuck owing themselves money. Either way it won=E2=
=80=99t be Sculptor=E2=80=99s problem; Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders will=
 get the money.=09There is no mention of a calculation shortfall so presuma=
bly everyone agrees on the numbers now.

Still Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has issues; it still thinks that there=E2=80=
=99s too much risk that the Weinstein deal won=E2=80=99t close. There are t=
wo ways to think about this risk.
One is =E2=80=A6=C2=A0well, look, I have   spent a   certain amount of   ti=
me around   here writing about Elon Musk, who is (among other things) an ec=
centric billionaire who sometimes offers to buy public companies and then c=
hanges his mind. It happens! There are suggestions, in Sculptor=E2=80=99s a=
nnouncement, that it thinks of Weinstein and Ackman and Lasry that way. Its=
 objections include:

Because members of the Consortium are providing the debt commitments for it=
s proposed debt financing, there is an increased risk that if circumstances=
 change prior to closing, the Consortium can use a failure to satisfy the d=
ebt financing conditions as a reason not to close the transaction.
The Consortium=E2=80=99s proposal caps its financial exposure in a damages =
action at $39.2 million should it breach and refuse to consummate the trans=
action, which caps the Consortium=E2=80=99s ultimate downside.

That is:
=09If Weinstein and friends change their minds (because market conditions o=
r Sculptor=E2=80=99s results change, for instance, or because their own fin=
ancial situations change, or just because they don=E2=80=99t want to do thi=
s anymore), they will have excuses to get out of the deal: They are the len=
ders in the deal, so they =E2=80=9Ccan use a failure to satisfy the debt fi=
nancing conditions=E2=80=9D as an excuse to get out. I don=E2=80=99t exactl=
y understand this: Sculptor doesn=E2=80=99t spell out what the debt financi=
ng conditions are, and debt financing commitments tend to be less condition=
al than merger agreements so it would be odd if this would really give them=
 an out. But, sure, if you were really=C2=A0looking=C2=A0to get out of a de=
al, it=E2=80=99s one more excuse.=09Anyway, even if they don=E2=80=99t have=
 an excuse to get out of the deal, they can walk away and pay just $39.2 mi=
llion in damages, which isn=E2=80=99t that much compared to what Sculptor=
=E2=80=99s shareholders might lose. Basically they=E2=80=99d get a $39.2 mi=
llion option to buy the company for $700ish million, and if things changed =
they could walk away.
  [2]



If you are Sculptor=E2=80=99s board, you have to weigh these risks against =
the extra $1.61 per share that Weinstein is offering, and I guess your weig=
hing comes down to questions like:
=09How flighty do you think Weinstein and friends are? How likely are they =
to change their minds?=09How risky do you think Sculptor=E2=80=99s business=
, and the market, are? How likely is it that circumstances will change and =
Weinstein will try to back out?=09How much do you think Weinstein actually =
wants the company? If he really wants to buy Sculptor, then his technical a=
bility to get out of the deal=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t matter that much. If he=
=E2=80=99s just looking for a cheap option, it does.

On that last question, there are some reasons to think Weinstein is serious=
. He=E2=80=99s been talking to Sculptor for months, he has gotten a bunch o=
f commitments from his hedge-fund-manager friends, he keeps raising his bid=
: It sure seems like he wants the company.
On the other hand, if you were being conspiratorial, you might say: Weinste=
in, Ackman and Lasry manage hedge funds that to some extent compete with Sc=
ulptor. It would be nice, for them, to buy a wounded rival at an attractive=
 price. But other outcomes might also be fine for them. If they agreed to b=
uy Sculptor, blew up the Rithm deal, and then backed out of their deal, tha=
t would be pretty disruptive for Sculptor=E2=80=99s employees and clients. =
Maybe everyone would get fed up with the uncertainty at Sculptor and leave.=
 Possibly spending $39.2 million to=C2=A0destroy a rival would be a better =
trade, for Weinstein and friends, than spending $700 million to=C2=A0buy=C2=
=A0it.
I don=E2=80=99t think that theory=C2=A0is right, but are a lot of big perso=
nalities and emotional dynamics here. Sculptor   has said that Och=E2=80=99=
s objections to its sale process are driven by =E2=80=9Cpersonal vendettas,=
=E2=80=9D specifically his desire for revenge on Jimmy Levin for (supposedl=
y) pushing him out of the firm he founded. For at least some people involve=
d in this process, the destruction of Sculptor would not be a good thing ex=
actly, but it might have certain consolations.
There is another, more straightforward way to think about the risk that the=
 Weinstein deal wouldn=E2=80=99t close. Sculptor manages about $34 billion =
of client funds, between multi-strategy and credit hedge funds, CLOs and re=
al estate private equity. It is the norm in asset management mergers to mak=
e the deal conditional on client consents: Nobody who buys Sculptor will wa=
nt it if all the clients leave, so before the deal closes they will ask the=
 clients to consent to the new management, and if too many clients say no t=
hen the deal won=E2=80=99t close.
  [3]
=C2=A0The Rithm deal is contingent on getting consents from 85% of clients =
(by revenue). The Weinstein deal would also be contingent on client consent=
s, though less than 85%.
  [4]

But Sculptor argues that clients would consent to Rithm (because it will re=
tain Jimmy Levin, whom they like, to run Sculptor=E2=80=99s funds) and woul=
d not consent to Weinstein:
The Consortium=E2=80=99s proposal requires Sculptor=E2=80=99s stockholders =
to take the risk that Sculptor=E2=80=99s fund investors will not approve of=
 Bidder J=E2=80=99s CEO and other outsiders having dominion over their capi=
tal. =C2=A0The idea that sophisticated institutional investors undertaking =
extensive due diligence will simply consent to a change of control which re=
sults in new personnel or a new =E2=80=9COffice of the CIO=E2=80=9D managin=
g their money (even where this =E2=80=9COffice=E2=80=9D includes certain me=
mbers of the existing investment team) is aspirational at best. Thus, the S=
pecial Committee is concerned about the Company=E2=80=99s ability to obtain=
 the consents required by the proposal, especially in light of client feedb=
ack received to date. =C2=A0If the Consortium believes that the Company=E2=
=80=99s clients would in fact grant their consent, then the Consortium, and=
 not Sculptor=E2=80=99s public stockholders, should bear the risk of obtain=
ing client consents.
That is, if you are a client of Sculptor at this point, you have demonstrat=
ed a certain willingness to let Jimmy Levin manage your money. You might be=
 equally happy to have Boaz Weinstein =E2=80=94=C2=A0or a group of managers=
 led by Boaz Weinstein, possibly including Levin =E2=80=94=C2=A0manage your=
 money, or you might not. (If you would be happier=C2=A0with Weinstein or A=
ckman or Lasry managing your money, probably you should just take your mone=
y out of Sculptor and invest it in their funds? No merger really required.)=
 But if Sculptor signed the deal with Weinstein and all its clients said no=
, then:
=09Weinstein and friends would have a contractual right to get out of the d=
eal;=09They would=C2=A0want=C2=A0to get out of the deal (because there=E2=
=80=99d be nothing for them to buy);=09The Rithm deal would be gone; and=09=
The clients would be gone, or at least very fed up, and Sculptor might not =
have much business left as an independent company.

That is a disaster outcome.
How do you address this risk? A few possible answers:
=09Ask the clients? Like, before you throw out the Rithm deal and sign with=
 Weinstein, call up your biggest clients and say =E2=80=9Chey would you be =
cool with this Weinstein deal?=E2=80=9D and see what they say. There are pr=
obably some issues with that =E2=80=94=C2=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s NDA with Wei=
nstein might limit its ability to do that, and it=E2=80=99s maybe an awkwar=
d hypothetical to pose to the clients =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does give you s=
ome information. Sculptor says that =E2=80=9Cclient feedback to date=E2=80=
=9D gives it concerns about getting client consent to the Weinstein deal, w=
hich presumably means that some of its clients have read news reports about=
 the situation and have called Sculptor up to say =E2=80=9Cnot Weinstein,=
=E2=80=9D but Sculptor is telling its side of the story and it doesn=E2=80=
=99t seem like they=E2=80=99ve done any systematic polling. =E2=80=9CThere =
is no indication that the Special Committee took any steps to test this hyp=
othesis,=E2=80=9D  Och said in one of his letters to the board last week.=
=09Let Weinstein ask the clients? Like, give him a list of the top 20 clien=
ts, release him from his NDA to pitch them, and see what he comes back with=
? If they all say yes then sure, whatever, do the deal? Again there are som=
e issues here =E2=80=94=C2=A0do you really want to let a rival hedge fund m=
anager pitch all your clients? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does help you get cert=
ainty.=09Do what the board says: Let =E2=80=9Cthe Consortium, and not Sculp=
tor=E2=80=99s public stockholders=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 bear the risk of obtaining=
 client consents.=E2=80=9D Agree to the Weinstein deal but=C2=A0without=C2=
=A0a client consent contingency; if all the clients say no then Weinstein s=
till has to pay $12.76 to buy the empty shell of Sculptor. That is unusual,=
 and a bit harsh =E2=80=94=C2=A0though, as they say, it=E2=80=99s not that =
harsh if Weinstein is very confident he can win over the clients.
  [5]



When we first talked about the Sculptor situation,   I began by saying that=
 =E2=80=9Cthere are not a lot of hostile takeovers of hedge funds.=E2=80=9D=
 This is why: If you run a hedge fund, and I run a hedge fund, presumably m=
