A traditional risk for investors in emerging-market sovereign bonds is that=
 a country might issue some bonds and then have a military coup, and the ne=
w rulers might decide not to pay off the bonds. A more modern risk is that =
the country might issue some green bonds, promising to do good environmenta=
l things with the proceeds, and the buyers of the bonds might be funds focu=
sed on environmental, social and governance issues. And then the country mi=
ght have a military coup, and:
=09The new rulers might decide not to pay off the bonds, or=09The new ruler=
s might keep paying the bonds, but start doing bad environmental things, or=
=09The new rulers might keep paying the bonds and doing green stuff, but if=
 you are an ESG investor, owning the performing green bonds of a military j=
unta does feel a bit less ESG-y than owning the performing green bonds of a=
 country with a democratically elected government. Arguably you have to kic=
k the bonds out of your ESG fund for=C2=A0governance=C2=A0reasons, even if =
they are still pretty green.

It=E2=80=99s just, you know, traditionally bond investors had one thing to =
worry about (getting paid), and now they have multiple incommensurable thin=
gs to worry about.
So here=E2=80=99s this:

The coup in Gabon sent investors scrambling to assess its impact on a new E=
SG debt contract that=E2=80=99s attracted investment-grade creditors to the=
=C2=A0junk issuer=E2=80=99s bond market.
The deal in question is a $500 million debt-for-nature swap, completed by=
=C2=A0Bank of America Corp.=C2=A0just two weeks ago. Under the terms of the=
 deal, Gabon refinanced a portion of its bonds at more favorable terms in e=
xchange for a marine conservation pledge.
A key feature of the swap is a political risk insurance contract from the U=
S International Development Finance Corp., which creditors can fall back on=
 if there=E2=80=99s a default, subject to arbitration. That could include G=
abon=E2=80=99s failure to repay its debt or meet conservation pledges. It=
=E2=80=99s the main reason that investors who normally wouldn=E2=80=99t ven=
ture into=C2=A0emerging markets=C2=A0were drawn to the deal. And while such=
 insurance contracts aren=E2=80=99t new, they=E2=80=99ve not yet been activ=
ated in the context of a debt-for-nature swap. =E2=80=A6
Soldiers seized power in Gabon this week, four days after the central Afric=
an nation held disputed presidential elections. The coup triggered a record=
 slump in Gabon=E2=80=99s mostly junk-rated international bonds.=C2=A0
But the=C2=A0bonds tied to its debt-for-nature swap, which are rated Aa2 by=
 Moody=E2=80=99s Investors Service,=C2=A0fared better. That=E2=80=99s despi=
te uncertainty surrounding not only repayment, but also the issuer=E2=80=99=
s ability to live up to its commitment to protect the environment. =E2=80=
=A6
The soldiers who seized power said in a state television broadcast on Wedne=
sday that all international agreements would be respected, without providin=
g details.

Technically Gabon=E2=80=99s bond is a =E2=80=9Cblue=E2=80=9D bond (about oc=
ean conservation) rather than a =E2=80=9Cgreen=E2=80=9D one, but you get th=
e idea.=C2=A0If Gabon doesn=E2=80=99t pay, the insurance contract pays out.=
 If Gabon=C2=A0does=C2=A0pay, but doesn=E2=80=99t meet its conservation ple=
dge, the insurance =E2=80=A6=C2=A0also pays out? Seems strange,
  [7]
 but in a world of green and blue=C2=A0bond investing I suppose those are t=
he risks you worry about.

