parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Weinstein and friends are still provid=
ing equity commitments.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Their deal=
 is no longer contingent on selling the CLO business to Bidder H. Presumabl=
y they still plan to sell it, but if they can=E2=80=99t that=E2=80=99s thei=
r problem.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Instead, Weinstein and =
friends will bridge the CLO business by lending themselves the money: =E2=
=80=9CMembers of the Consortium are providing the debt commitments for its =
proposed debt financing.=E2=80=9D That is, the deal will be funded by (roug=
hly) half equity commitments from Weinstein and friends, and half=C2=A0<em>=
loans=C2=A0</em>from them. If they sell the CLO business quickly, they=E2=
=80=99ll use the money to pay back the loans. If not, they=E2=80=99ll be st=
uck owing themselves money. Either way it won=E2=80=99t be Sculptor=E2=80=
=99s problem; Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders will get the money.</li>=09<l=
i style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">There is no mention of a calculation shortf=
all so presumably everyone agrees on the numbers now.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has issues; it =
still thinks that there=E2=80=99s too much risk that the Weinstein deal won=
=E2=80=99t close. There are two ways to think about this risk.</p>
