ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  here</a> writing about Elon M=
usk, who is (among other things) an eccentric billionaire who sometimes off=
ers to buy public companies and then changes his mind. It happens! There ar=
e suggestions, in Sculptor=E2=80=99s announcement, that it thinks of Weinst=
ein and Ackman and Lasry that way. Its objections include:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because members of the Consortium are providin=
g the debt commitments for its proposed debt financing, there is an increas=
ed risk that if circumstances change prior to closing, the Consortium can u=
se a failure to satisfy the debt financing conditions as a reason not to cl=
ose the transaction.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Consortium=E2=80=99s proposal caps its fin=
ancial exposure in a damages action at $39.2 million should it breach and r=
efuse to consummate the transaction, which caps the Consortium=E2=80=99s ul=
timate downside.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If Weinstein and friends change their =
minds (because market conditions or Sculptor=E2=80=99s results change, for =
instance, or because their own financial situations change, or just because=
 they don=E2=80=99t want to do this anymore), they will have excuses to get=
 out of the deal: They are the lenders in the deal, so they =E2=80=9Ccan us=
e a failure to satisfy the debt financing conditions=E2=80=9D as an excuse =
to get out. I don=E2=80=99t exactly understand this: Sculptor doesn=E2=80=
=99t spell out what the debt financing conditions are, and debt financing c=
ommitments tend to be less conditional than merger agreements so it would b=
e odd if this would really give them an out. But, sure, if you were really=
=C2=A0<em>looking=C2=A0</em>to get out of a deal, it=E2=80=99s one more exc=
use.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Anyway, even if they don=E2=
=80=99t have an excuse to get out of the deal, they can walk away and pay j=
ust $39.2 million in damages, which isn=E2=80=99t that much compared to wha=
t Sculptor=E2=80=99s shareholders might lose. Basically they=E2=80=99d get =
a $39.2 million option to buy the company for $700ish million, and if thing=
s changed they could walk away.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnot=
e-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !imp=
ortant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are Sculptor=E2=80=99s board, you have =
to weigh these risks against the extra $1.61 per share that Weinstein is of=
fering, and I guess your weighing comes down to questions like:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">How flighty do you think Weinstein an=
d friends are? How likely are they to change their minds?</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">How risky do you think Sculptor=E2=80=99s business=
, and the market, are? How likely is it that circumstances will change and =
Weinstein will try to back out?</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ho=
w much do you think Weinstein actually wants the company? If he really want=
s to buy Sculptor, then his technical ability to get out of the deal=C2=A0d=
oesn=E2=80=99t matter that much. If he=E2=80=99s just looking for a cheap o=
ption, it does.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On that last question, there are some reasons =
to think Weinstein is serious. He=E2=80=99s been talking to Sculptor for mo=
nths, he has gotten a bunch of commitments from his hedge-fund-manager frie=
nds, he keeps raising his bid: It sure seems like he wants the company.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On the other hand, if you were being conspirat=
orial, you might say: Weinstein, Ackman and Lasry manage hedge funds that t=
o some extent compete with Sculptor. It would be nice, for them, to buy a w=
ounded rival at an attractive price. But other outcomes might also be fine =
for them. If they agreed to buy Sculptor, blew up the Rithm deal, and then =
backed out of their deal, that would be pretty disruptive for Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s employees and clients. Maybe everyone would get fed up with the unc=
ertainty at Sculptor and leave. Possibly spending $39.2 million to=C2=A0<em=
>destroy </em>a rival would be a better trade, for Weinstein and friends, t=
han spending $700 million to=C2=A0<em>buy=C2=A0</em>it.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that theory=C2=A0is righ=
t, but are a lot of big personalities and emotional dynamics here. Sculptor=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32571530.259423/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMzAvc2N1=
bHB0b3ItaXMtZnVsbC1vZi1jb25mbGljdHM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDgzMTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXR=
tX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwODMxJnV0bV=
9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cD6629402c" itemprop=3D"S=
toryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000=
; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom=
-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  has=
 said</a> that Och=E2=80=99s objections to its sale process are driven by =
=E2=80=9Cpersonal vendettas,=E2=80=9D specifically his desire for revenge o=
n Jimmy Levin for (supposedly) pushing him out of the firm he founded. For =
at least some people involved in this process, the destruction of Sculptor =
would not be a good thing exactly, but it might have certain consolations.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There is another, more straightforward way to =
think about the risk that the Weinstein deal wouldn=E2=80=99t close. Sculpt=
or manages about $34 billion of client funds, between multi-strategy and cr=
edit hedge funds, CLOs and real estate private equity. It is the norm in as=
set management mergers to make the deal conditional on client consents: Nob=
ody who buys Sculptor will want it if all the clients leave, so before the =
deal closes they will ask the clients to consent to the new management, and=
 if too many clients say no then the deal won=E2=80=99t close.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0The Rithm deal is contingent on getting consents from 85% of clie=
nts (by revenue). The Weinstein deal would also be contingent on client con=
sents, though less than 85%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Sculptor argues that clients would consent=
 to Rithm (because it will retain Jimmy Levin, whom they like, to run Sculp=
tor=E2=80=99s funds) and would not consent to Weinstein:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Consortium=E2=80=99s proposal =
requires Sculptor=E2=80=99s stockholders to take the risk that Sculptor=E2=
=80=99s fund investors will not approve of Bidder J=E2=80=99s CEO and other=
 outsiders having dominion over their capital. =C2=A0The idea that sophisti=
cated institutional investors undertaking extensive due diligence will simp=
ly consent to a change of control which results in new personnel or a new =
=E2=80=9COffice of the CIO=E2=80=9D managing their money (even where this =
=E2=80=9COffice=E2=80=9D includes certain members of the existing investmen=
t team) is aspirational at best. Thus, the Special Committee is concerned a=
bout the Company=E2=80=99s ability to obtain the consents required by the p=
roposal, especially in light of client feedback received to date. =C2=A0If =
the Consortium believes that the Company=E2=80=99s clients would in fact gr=
ant their consent, then the Consortium, and not Sculptor=E2=80=99s public s=
tockholders, should bear the risk of obtaining client consents.</p></blockq=
uote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is, if you are a client of Sculptor at th=
is point, you have demonstrated a certain willingness to let Jimmy Levin ma=
nage your money. You might be equally happy to have Boaz Weinstein =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0or a group of managers led by Boaz Weinstein, possibly including L=
evin =E2=80=94=C2=A0manage your money, or you might not. (If you would be <=
em>happier=C2=A0</em>with Weinstein or Ackman or Lasry managing your money,=
 probably you should just take your money out of Sculptor and invest it in =
their funds? No merger really required.) But if Sculptor signed the deal wi=
th Weinstein and all its clients said no, then:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Weinstein and friends would have a co=
ntractual right to get out of the deal;</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">They would=C2=A0<em>want=C2=A0</em>to get out of the deal (because th=
ere=E2=80=99d be nothing for them to buy);</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The Rithm deal would be gone; and</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-botto=
m: 5px;">The clients would be gone, or at least very fed up, and Sculptor m=
ight not have much business left as an independent company.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That is a disaster outcome.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How do you address this risk? A few possible a=
nswers:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ask the clients? Like, before you thro=
w out the Rithm deal and sign with Weinstein, call up your biggest clients =
and say =E2=80=9Chey would you be cool with this Weinstein deal?=E2=80=9D a=
nd see what they say. There are probably some issues with that =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0Sculptor=E2=80=99s NDA with Weinstein might limit its ability to do that=
, and it=E2=80=99s maybe an awkward hypothetical to pose to the clients =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0but it does give you some information. Sculptor says that =E2=
=80=9Cclient feedback to date=E2=80=9D gives it concerns about getting clie=
nt consent to the Weinstein deal, which presumably means that some of its c=
lients have read news reports about the situation and have called Sculptor =
up to say =E2=80=9Cnot Weinstein,=E2=80=9D but Sculptor is telling its side=
 of the story and it doesn=E2=80=99t seem like they=E2=80=99ve done any sys=
tematic polling. =E2=80=9CThere is no indication that the Special Committee=
 took any steps to test this hypothesis,=E2=80=9D <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32571530.259423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9=
BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MDMyNTYvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIzMjE4MDE4L2Q1MDk2NDhkZX=
g5OTI5Lmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc826118b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Och said</a> in on=
e of his letters to the board last week.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">Let Weinstein ask the clients? Like, give him a list of the top 20 c=
lients, release him from his NDA to pitch them, and see what he comes back =
with? If they all say yes then sure, whatever, do the deal? Again there are=
 some issues here =E2=80=94=C2=A0do you really want to let a rival hedge fu=
nd manager pitch all your clients? =E2=80=94=C2=A0but it does help you get =
certainty.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Do what the board says:=
 Let =E2=80=9Cthe Consortium, and not Sculptor=E2=80=99s public stockholder=
s=C2=A0=E2=80=A6 bear the risk of obtaining client consents.=E2=80=9D Agree=
 to the Weinstein deal but=C2=A0<em>without=C2=A0</em>a client consent cont=
ingency; if all the clients say no then Weinstein still has to pay $12.76 t=
o buy the empty shell of Sculptor. That is unusual, and a bit harsh =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0though, as they say, it=E2=80=99s not that harsh if Weinstein is v=
ery confident he can win over the clients.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a>
</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">When we first talked about the Sculptor situat=
ion, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/32571530.2594=
23/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMjEv=
ZXZlcnlvbmUtd2FudHMtYS1waWVjZS1vZi1zY3VscHRvcj9jbXBpZD1CQkQwODMxMjNfTU9ORVl=
TVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMz=
A4MzEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cC8a4530a3" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;">  I began</a> by saying that =E2=80=9Cthere are not a lot of hostile =
takeovers of hedge funds.=E2=80=9D This is why: If you run a hedge fund, an=
d I run a hedge fund, presumably my clients want me to manage their money a=
nd your clients want you to manage their money. If I buy all the shares of =
your hedge fund management company and say to your clients =E2=80=9Chey guy=
s, I manage your money now,=E2=80=9D they might say =E2=80=9Cno you don=E2=
=80=99t.=E2=80=9D Sculptor=E2=80=99s clients are clients of the firm, but t=
hey are also clients of Jimmy Levin, and it=E2=80=99s not clear if they wou=
ld go with the firm or with the guy. Sculptor=E2=80=99s board has obligatio=
ns to get the best deal for its public shareholders, but that does require =
trying to figure out what the hedge fund clients want.</p>
