<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A traditional risk for investors in emerging-m=
arket sovereign bonds is that a country might issue some bonds and then hav=
e a military coup, and the new rulers might decide not to pay off the bonds=
. A more modern risk is that the country might issue some green bonds, prom=
ising to do good environmental things with the proceeds, and the buyers of =
the bonds might be funds focused on environmental, social and governance is=
sues. And then the country might have a military coup, and:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The new rulers might decide not to pa=
y off the bonds, or</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The new rulers=
 might keep paying the bonds, but start doing bad environmental things, or<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The new rulers might keep paying t=
he bonds and doing green stuff, but if you are an ESG investor, owning the =
performing green bonds of a military junta does feel a bit less ESG-y than =
owning the performing green bonds of a country with a democratically electe=
d government. Arguably you have to kick the bonds out of your ESG fund for=
=C2=A0<em>governance=C2=A0</em>reasons, even if they are still pretty green=
.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s just, you know, traditionally bon=
d investors had one thing to worry about (getting paid), and now they have =
multiple incommensurable things to worry about.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/32571530.259423/aHR0cHM6Ly9ibGlua3MuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL3N0=
b3JpZXMvUzA3SU43RFdYMlBTP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA4MzEyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW0=
9ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDgzMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ2=
49bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2724626f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">So here=E2=80=
=99s this</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The coup in Gabon sent investors scrambling to=
 assess its impact on a new ESG debt contract that=E2=80=99s attracted inve=
stment-grade creditors to the=C2=A0junk issuer=E2=80=99s bond market.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The deal in question is a $500 million debt-fo=
r-nature swap, completed by=C2=A0Bank of America Corp.=C2=A0just two weeks =
ago. Under the terms of the deal, Gabon refinanced a portion of its bonds a=
t more favorable terms in exchange for a marine conservation pledge.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A key feature of the swap is a political risk =
insurance contract from the US International Development Finance Corp., whi=
ch creditors can fall back on if there=E2=80=99s a default, subject to arbi=
tration. That could include Gabon=E2=80=99s failure to repay its debt or me=
et conservation pledges. It=E2=80=99s the main reason that investors who no=
rmally wouldn=E2=80=99t venture into=C2=A0emerging markets=C2=A0were drawn =
to the deal. And while such insurance contracts aren=E2=80=99t new, they=E2=
=80=99ve not yet been activated in the context of a debt-for-nature swap. =
=E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Soldiers seized power in Gabon this week, four=
 days after the central African nation held disputed presidential elections=
. The coup triggered a record slump in Gabon=E2=80=99s mostly junk-rated in=
ternational bonds.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the=C2=A0bonds tied to its debt-for-nature=
 swap, which are rated Aa2 by Moody=E2=80=99s Investors Service,=C2=A0fared=
 better. That=E2=80=99s despite uncertainty surrounding not only repayment,=
 but also the issuer=E2=80=99s ability to live up to its commitment to prot=
ect the environment. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The soldiers who seized power said in a state =
television broadcast on Wednesday that all international agreements would b=
e respected, without providing details.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Technically Gabon=E2=80=99s bond is a =E2=80=
=9Cblue=E2=80=9D bond (about ocean conservation) rather than a =E2=80=9Cgre=
en=E2=80=9D one, but you get the idea.=C2=A0If Gabon doesn=E2=80=99t pay, t=
he insurance contract pays out. If Gabon=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>pay, but d=
oesn=E2=80=99t meet its conservation pledge, the insurance =E2=80=A6=C2=A0a=
lso pays out? Seems strange,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7=
" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-=
width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !import=
ant; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a> but in a world of green and blue=C2=A0bond investing I suppose those a=
re the risks you worry about.</p>
